The Ukraine on the Path to Europe
"East is East and West is West, and they will never meet," Rudyard Kipling once said.
While Ukraine is undoubtedly in the east, it is in Eastern Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the dominant goal for many of us.
However, the road there was not always paved with success, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 showed that Ukrainians are still determined to go down this path.
I am a Social Democrat and was never a member of the communist party, although as a lawyer during the Soviet era I was quite successful.
It is beyond question for me that our "Soviet" legacy is largely responsible for Ukraine's difficulties in catching up with Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural areas were practically paralyzed by outdated machine parks and the inertia of state-run agriculture in the Soviet mold.
The rural population sank deeply into dirt and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is enormous.
But our Soviet heritage does not justify everything.
We have completely bungled the reform.
For often we wanted to import proven concepts from the West – private property, free market economy, strict observance of human rights, the creation of civil society, representative democracy – in watered-down form and thought that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Supreme Council (the Parliament of Ukraine) over the years has adopted citizen rights and criminal law, land, family, and economic rights, which amounts to something like a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that was cut off from European history for centuries was often painful, but it has come into swing, even though we do not see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-oriented, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Still, we are Europeans.
This is evident on the streets and squares of Kyiv.
Today, drivers let pedestrians cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to take refuge from thoughtless drivers).
In Kyiv, there is now a lively café scene and friendly public squares where people can stop and enjoy life.
Young people are learning English, German, and French; they can use computers and surf the internet in internet cafes.
But these are just the ramblings of someone who loves Kyiv very much.
The sober eye of the professional politician I am sees deeper changes.
In the last ten years, a development has taken place from total rejection of reforms to a policy of half-hearted reforms motivated by corrupt motives, and finally to a gradual introduction of Western practices.
Administrative reform reflects this very clearly.
Initially, the state reform elicited hostile sentiment among both bureaucrats and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and thoughtless reduction of public servants began.
It was a "model F" reform: the state must shrink, it was assumed, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one thought about how countries like France or Switzerland manage to thrive with large state apparatuses.
The problem is not just one of size, but also of organization and effectiveness.
Realizing that the government does not necessarily become better simply by drawing with a red pen led us to the second stage in our reform process.
Gradually, the state was reformed in a more considered manner.
New departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
As a result, the work of the government ministries was stabilized.
At first, the authority granted to these new areas was too broad to effectively streamline their work.
Now they function more or less normally.
Ukrainians might sometimes be annoyed by these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they increasingly accept them as necessary (although unwillingly).
Rational politicians also accept them.
Only radicals and populists – there are still too many of them among us – can afford to adopt a indifferent attitude towards a more efficient state.
Taming our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
Ukraine was for too long a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire, the most important but still a province.
This has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
A overwhelming sense of inferiority and our efforts to deny this have led to some of the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincialist cannot admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
The more we shed our provincial impulse to defend ourselves, the more open we become to the best that others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, Ukrainians have had to recognize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, perhaps we ourselves contributed to becoming even more sickly, but the recent elections, which brought the Communists down from their dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly reduced the power of the "powerful parties," have pushed our provincial radicals to the margins of politics.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders, or at least as a people on the edge of Europe, we want to build a society where there are no outsiders or边缘人.
As the great and already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all nature's achievements, the most astonishing probably is the survival of the weakest."
The long, arduous journey towards Europe has helped a weak new nation become strong and survive.
